# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: measure-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] In measure theory (a branch of mathematical analysis), a property holds **almost everywhere** if, in a technical sense, the set for which the property holds takes up nearly all possibilities.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] The notion of "almost everywhere" is a companion notion to the concept of measure zero, and is analogous to the notion of *almost surely* in probability theory.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] More specifically, a property holds almost everywhere if it holds for all elements in a set except a subset of measure zero, or equivalently, if the set of elements for which the property holds is conull.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] In cases where the measure is not complete, it is sufficient that the set be contained within a set of measure zero.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] When discussing sets of real numbers, the Lebesgue measure is usually assumed unless otherwise stated.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] The term *almost everywhere* is abbreviated *a.e.*; in older literature *p.p.* is used, to stand for the equivalent French phrase *presque partout*.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] A set with **full measure** is one whose complement is of measure zero.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] In probability theory, the terms *almost surely*, *almost certain* and *almost always* refer to events with probability 1 not necessarily including all of the outcomes.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] These are exactly the sets of full measure in a probability space.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] Occasionally, instead of saying that a property holds almost everywhere, it is said that the property holds for **almost all** elements (though the term almost all can also have other meanings).
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] If $(X,\Sigma ,\mu )$ is a measure space, a property P is said to hold almost everywhere in X if there exists a measurable set $N\in \Sigma$ with $\mu (N)=0$ , and all $x\in X\setminus N$ have the property P .
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] Another common way of expressing the same thing is to say that "almost every point satisfies $P\,$ ", or that "for almost every x , $P(x)$ holds".
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] It is *not* required that the set $\{x\in X:\neg P(x)\}$ has measure zero; it may not be measurable.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] By the above definition, it is sufficient that $\{x\in X:\neg P(x)\}$ be contained in some set N that is measurable and has measure zero.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] However, this technicality vanishes when considering a complete measure space: if X is complete then N exists with measure zero if and only if $\{x\in X:\neg P(x)\}$ is measurable with measure zero.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] As a consequence of the first two properties, it is often possible to reason about "almost every point" of a measure space as though it were an ordinary point rather than an abstraction.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] This is often done implicitly in informal mathematical arguments.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] However, one must be careful with this mode of reasoning because of the third bullet above: universal quantification over uncountable families of statements is valid for ordinary points but not for "almost every point".
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] Outside of the context of real analysis, the notion of a property true almost everywhere is sometimes defined in terms of an ultrafilter.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] A property *P* of points in *X* holds almost everywhere, relative to an ultrafilter *F*, if the set of points for which *P* holds is in *F*.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] For example, one construction of the hyperreal number system defines a hyperreal number as an equivalence class of sequences that are equal almost everywhere as defined by an ultrafilter.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] The definition of *almost everywhere* in terms of ultrafilters is closely related to the definition in terms of measures, because each ultrafilter defines a finitely-additive measure taking only the values 0 and 1, where a set has measure 1 if and only if it is included in the ultrafilter.
[src:measure-theory/almost-everywhere] With this notion of "almost everywhere" Łoś's theorem can be understood as saying that a first-order formula is true in an ultraproduct if and only if it's true in almost all of the factors.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] In mathematics, the **Borel sets** of a topological space are a particular class of "well-behaved" subsets of that space.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] For example, whereas an arbitrary subset of the real numbers might fail to be Lebesgue measurable, every Borel set of reals is universally measurable.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] Which sets are Borel can be specified in a number of equivalent ways.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] The most usual definition goes through the notion of a σ-algebra, which is a collection of subsets of a topological space X that contains both the empty set and the entire set X , and is closed under countable union and complement.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] Then we can define the **Borel σ-algebra** over X to be the smallest σ-algebra containing all open sets of X .
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] A Borel subset of X is then simply an element of this σ-algebra.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] Borel sets are important in measure theory, since any measure defined on the open sets of a space, or on the closed sets of a space, must also be defined on all Borel sets of that space.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] Any measure defined on the Borel sets is called a Borel measure.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] Borel sets and the associated Borel hierarchy also play a fundamental role in descriptive set theory.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] In some contexts, Borel sets are defined to be generated by the compact sets of the topological space, rather than the open sets.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] The two definitions are equivalent for many well-behaved spaces, including all Hausdorff σ-compact spaces, but can be different in more pathological spaces.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] In the case that X is a metric space, the Borel algebra in the first sense may be described *generatively* as follows.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] The claim is that the Borel algebra is $G^{\omega _{1}}$ , where ${\omega _{1}}$ is the first uncountable ordinal number.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] That is, the Borel algebra can be *generated* from the class of open sets by iterating the operation $G\mapsto G_{\delta \sigma }$ to the first uncountable ordinal.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] To prove this claim, any open set in a metric space is the union of an increasing sequence of closed sets.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] In particular, complementation of sets maps $G^{m}$ into itself for any limit ordinal m ; moreover if m is an uncountable limit ordinal, $G^{m}$ is closed under countable unions.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] For each Borel set B , there is some countable ordinal $\alpha _{B}$ such that B can be obtained by iterating the operation over $\alpha _{B}$ .
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] However, as B varies over all Borel sets, $\alpha _{B}$ will vary over all the countable ordinals, and thus the first ordinal at which all the Borel sets are obtained is $\omega _{1}$ , the first uncountable ordinal.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] The resulting sequence of sets is termed the Borel hierarchy.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] An important example, especially in the theory of probability, is the Borel algebra on the set of real numbers.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] It is the algebra on which the Borel measure is defined.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] Given a real random variable defined on a probability space, its probability distribution is by definition also a measure on the Borel algebra.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] The Borel algebra on the reals is the smallest σ-algebra on $\mathbb {R}$ that contains all the intervals.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] In the construction by transfinite induction, it can be shown that, in each step, the number of sets is, at most, the cardinality of the continuum.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] In fact, the cardinality of the collection of Borel sets is equal to that of the continuum (compare to the number of Lebesgue measurable sets that exist, which is strictly larger and equal to $2^{2^{\aleph _{0}}}$ ).
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] The **Borel space** associated to X is the pair $(X,{\mathcal {B}})$ , where ${\mathcal {B}}$ is the σ-algebra of Borel sets of X .
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] George Mackey defined a Borel space somewhat differently, writing that it is "a set together with a distinguished σ-field of subsets called its Borel sets." However, modern usage is to call the distinguished sub-algebra the *measurable sets* and such spaces *measurable spaces*.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] The reason for this distinction is that the Borel sets are the σ-algebra generated by *open* sets (of a topological space), whereas Mackey's definition refers to a set equipped with an *arbitrary* σ-algebra.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] There exist measurable spaces that are not Borel spaces, for any choice of topology on the underlying space.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] Measurable spaces form a category in which the morphisms are measurable functions between measurable spaces.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] A function $f:X\rightarrow Y$ is measurable if it pulls back measurable sets, i.e., for all measurable sets B in Y , the set $f^{-1}(B)$ is measurable in X .
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] Considered as Borel spaces, the real line **$\mathbb {R}$ ,** the union of **$\mathbb {R}$** with a countable set, and **$\mathbb {R} ^{n}$** are isomorphic.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] A **standard Borel space** is the Borel space associated to a Polish space.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] A standard Borel space is characterized up to isomorphism by its cardinality, and any uncountable standard Borel space has the cardinality of the continuum.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] For subsets of Polish spaces, Borel sets can be characterized as those sets that are the ranges of continuous injective maps defined on Polish spaces.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] Note however, that the range of a continuous noninjective map may fail to be Borel.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] Every probability measure on a standard Borel space turns it into a standard probability space.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] An example of a subset of the reals that is non-Borel, due to Lusin, is described below.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] In contrast, an example of a non-measurable set cannot be exhibited, although the existence of such a set is implied, for example, by the axiom of choice.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] where $a_{0}$ is some integer and all the other numbers $a_{k}$ are *positive* integers.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] Let A be the set of all irrational numbers that correspond to sequences $(a_{0},a_{1},\dots )$ with the following property: there exists an infinite subsequence $(a_{k_{0}},a_{k_{1}},\dots )$ such that each element is a divisor of the next element.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] However, it is analytic (all Borel sets are also analytic), and complete in the class of analytic sets.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] It's important to note, that while Zermelo–Fraenkel axioms (ZF) are sufficient to formalize the construction of A , it cannot be proven in ZF alone that A is non-Borel.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] In fact, it is consistent with ZF that $\mathbb {R}$ is a countable union of countable sets, so that any subset of $\mathbb {R}$ is a Borel set.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] Another non-Borel set is an inverse image $f^{-1}[0]$ of an infinite parity function $f\colon \{0,1\}^{\omega }\to \{0,1\}$ .
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] However, this is a proof of existence (via the axiom of choice), not an explicit example.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] According to Paul Halmos, a subset of a locally compact Hausdorff topological space is called a *Borel set* if it belongs to the smallest σ-ring containing all compact sets.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] Norberg and Vervaat redefine the Borel algebra of a topological space X as the $\sigma$ -algebra generated by its open subsets and its compact saturated subsets.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] This definition is well-suited for applications in the case where X is not Hausdorff.
[src:measure-theory/borel-set] It coincides with the usual definition if X is second countable or if every compact saturated subset is closed (which is the case in particular if X is Hausdorff).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] In mathematics, the integral of a non-negative function of a single variable can be regarded, in the simplest case, as the area between the graph of that function and the x-axis.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The **Lebesgue integral**, named after French mathematician Henri Lebesgue, is one way to make this concept rigorous and to extend it to more general functions.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The Lebesgue integral is more general than the Riemann integral, which it largely replaced in mathematical analysis since the first half of the 20th century.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] It can accommodate functions with discontinuities arising in many applications that are pathological from the perspective of the Riemann integral.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The Lebesgue integral also has generally better analytical properties.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] For instance, under mild conditions, it is possible to exchange limits with Lebesgue integration, while the conditions for doing this with a Riemann integral are comparatively restrictive.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Furthermore, the Lebesgue integral can be generalized in a straightforward way to more general spaces, measure spaces, such as those that arise in probability theory.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The term **Lebesgue integration** can mean either the general theory of integration of a function with respect to a general measure, as introduced by Lebesgue, or the specific case of integration of a function defined on a sub-domain of the real line with respect to the Lebesgue measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The integral of a positive real function f between boundaries a and b can be interpreted as the area under the graph of f, between a and b.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] This notion of area fits some functions, mainly piecewise continuous functions, including elementary functions, for example polynomials.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] However, the graphs of other functions, for example the Dirichlet function, do not fit well with the notion of area.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Graphs like that of the latter raise the question, "For which class of functions does 'area under the curve' make sense?".
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The answer to this question has great theoretical importance.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] As part of a general movement toward rigor in mathematics in the nineteenth century, mathematicians attempted to put integral calculus on a firm foundation.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The Riemann integral—proposed by Bernhard Riemann (1826–1866)—is a broadly successful attempt to provide such a foundation.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Riemann's definition starts with the construction of a sequence of easily calculated areas that converge to the integral of a given function.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] This definition is successful in the sense that it gives the expected answer for many already-solved problems, and gives useful results for many other problems.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] However, Riemann integration does not interact well with taking limits of sequences of functions, making such limiting processes difficult to analyze.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] This is important, for instance, in the study of Fourier series, Fourier transforms, and other topics.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The Lebesgue integral describes better how and when it is possible to take limits under the integral sign (via the monotone convergence theorem and dominated convergence theorem).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] While the Riemann integral considers the area under a curve as made out of vertical rectangles, the Lebesgue definition considers horizontal slabs that are not necessarily just rectangles, and so it is more flexible.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] For this reason, the Lebesgue definition makes it possible to calculate integrals for a broader class of functions.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] For example, the Dirichlet function, which is 1 where its argument is rational and 0 otherwise, has a Lebesgue integral, but does not have a Riemann integral.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Furthermore, the Lebesgue integral of this function is zero, which agrees with the intuition that when picking a real number uniformly at random from the unit interval, the probability of picking a rational number should be zero.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The insight is that one should be able to rearrange the values of a function freely, while preserving the value of the integral.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] This process of rearrangement can convert a very pathological function into one that is "nice" from the point of view of integration, and thus let such pathological functions be integrated.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Folland (1999) summarizes the difference between the Riemann and Lebesgue approaches thus: "to compute the Riemann integral of f, one partitions the domain [*a*, *b*] into subintervals", while in the Lebesgue integral, "one is in effect partitioning the range of *f*".
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] For the Riemann integral, the *domain* is partitioned into intervals, and bars are constructed to meet the height of the graph.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The areas of these bars are added together, and this approximates the integral, in effect by summing areas of the form *f*(*x*)*dx* where *f*(*x*) is the height of a rectangle and dx is its width.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] For the Lebesgue integral, the *range* is partitioned into intervals, and so the region under the graph is partitioned into horizontal "slabs" (which may not be connected sets).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The area of a small horizontal "slab" under the graph of f, of height dy, is equal to the measure of the slab's width times dy: $\mu \left(\{x\mid f(x)>y\}\right)\,dy.$ The Lebesgue integral may then be defined by adding up the areas of these horizontal slabs.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] From this perspective, a key difference with the Riemann integral is that the "slabs" are no longer rectangular (cartesian products of two intervals), but instead are cartesian products of a measurable set with an interval.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] An equivalent way to introduce the Lebesgue integral is to use so-called simple functions, which generalize the step functions of Riemann integration.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Consider, for example, determining the cumulative COVID-19 case count from a graph of smoothed cases each day (right).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Partition the domain (time period) into intervals (eight, in the example) and construct bars with heights that meet the graph.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The cumulative count is found by summing, over all bars, the product of interval width (time in days) and the bar height (cases per day).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Choose a finite number of target values (eight, in the example) in the range of the function.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] By constructing bars with heights equal to these values, but below the function, they imply a partitioning of the domain into the same number of subsets (subsets, indicated by color in the example, need not be connected).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] This is a "simple function", as described below.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] on that subset (total time in days) and the bar height (cases per day).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] One can think of the Lebesgue integral either in terms of *slabs* or *simple functions*.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Intuitively, the area under a simple function can be partitioned into slabs based on the (finite) collection of values in the range of a simple function (a real interval).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Conversely, the (finite) collection of slabs in the undergraph of the function can be rearranged after a finite repartitioning to be the undergraph of a simple function.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The *slabs* viewpoint makes it easy to define the Lebesgue integral, in terms of basic calculus.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Suppose that *f* is a (Lebesgue measurable) function, taking non-negative values (possibly including +∞).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Define the distribution function of *f* as the "width of a slab", i.e., $F(y)=\mu \{x|f(x)>y\}.$ Then *F*(*y*) is monotone decreasing and non-negative, and therefore has an (improper) Riemann integral over (0, ∞), allowing that the integral can be +∞.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The Lebesgue integral can then be *defined* by $\int f\,d\mu =\int _{0}^{\infty }F(y)\,dy$ where the integral on the right is an ordinary improper Riemann integral, of a non-negative function (interpreted appropriately as +∞ if *F*(*y*) = +∞ on a neighborhood of 0).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Most textbooks, however, emphasize the *simple functions* viewpoint, because it is then more straightforward to prove the basic theorems about the Lebesgue integral.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Measure theory was initially created to provide a useful abstraction of the notion of length of subsets of the real line—and, more generally, area and volume of subsets of Euclidean spaces.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] In particular, it provided a systematic answer to the question of which subsets of **R** have a length.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] As later set theory developments showed (see non-measurable set), it is actually impossible to assign a length to all subsets of **R** in a way that preserves some natural additivity and translation invariance properties.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] This suggests that picking out a suitable class of *measurable* subsets is an essential prerequisite.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The Riemann integral uses the notion of length explicitly.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Indeed, the element of calculation for the Riemann integral is the rectangle [*a*, *b*] × [*c*, *d*], whose area is calculated to be (*b* − *a*)(*d* − *c*).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The quantity *b* − *a* is the length of the base of the rectangle and *d* − *c* is the height of the rectangle.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Riemann could only use planar rectangles to approximate the area under the curve, because there was no adequate theory for measuring more general sets.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] In the development of the theory in most modern textbooks (after 1950), the approach to measure and integration is *axiomatic*.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] This means that a measure is any function μ defined on a certain class X of subsets of a set E, which satisfies a certain list of properties.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] These properties can be shown to hold in many different cases.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] We start with a measure space (*E*, *X*, *μ*) where E is a set, X is a σ-algebra of subsets of E, and μ is a (non-negative) measure on E defined on the sets of X.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] For example, E can be Euclidean *n*-space **R***n* or some Lebesgue measurable subset of it, X is the σ-algebra of all Lebesgue measurable subsets of E, and *μ* is the Lebesgue measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] In the mathematical theory of probability, we confine our study to a probability measure *μ*, which satisfies *μ*(*E*) = 1.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Lebesgue's theory defines integrals for a class of functions called measurable functions.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] We can show that this is equivalent to requiring that the pre-image of any Borel subset of **R** be in X.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The theory of the Lebesgue integral requires a theory of measurable sets and measures on these sets, as well as a theory of measurable functions and integrals on these functions.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] One approach to constructing the Lebesgue integral is to make use of so-called *simple functions*: finite, real linear combinations of *indicator functions*.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Simple functions that lie directly underneath a given function f can be constructed by partitioning the range of f into a finite number of layers.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The intersection of the graph of f with a layer identifies a set of intervals in the domain of f, which, taken together, is defined to be the preimage of the lower bound of that layer, under the simple function.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] In this way, the partitioning of the range of f implies a partitioning of its domain.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The integral of a non-negative general measurable function is then defined as an appropriate supremum of approximations by simple functions, and the integral of a (not necessarily positive) measurable function is the difference of two integrals of non-negative measurable functions.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Notice that the result may be equal to +∞, unless *μ* is a *finite* measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] A finite linear combination of indicator functions $\sum _{k}a_{k}1_{S_{k}}$ where the coefficients ak are real numbers and *S**k* are disjoint measurable sets, is called a measurable simple function.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] We extend the integral by linearity to *non-negative* measurable simple functions.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] A simple function can be written in different ways as a linear combination of indicator functions, but the integral will be the same by the additivity of measures.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Some care is needed when defining the integral of a *real-valued* simple function, to avoid the undefined expression ∞ − ∞: one assumes that the representation $f=\sum _{k}a_{k}1_{S_{k}}$ is such that *μ*(*S**k*) < ∞ whenever *a**k* ≠ 0.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Then the above formula for the integral of f makes sense, and the result does not depend upon the particular representation of f satisfying the assumptions.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Let f be a non-negative measurable function on E, which we allow to attain the value +∞, in other words, f takes non-negative values in the extended real number line.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] We need to show this integral coincides with the preceding one, defined on the set of simple functions, when E is a segment [*a*, *b*].
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] There is also the question of whether this corresponds in any way to a Riemann notion of integration.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] It is possible to prove that the answer to both questions is yes.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] We have defined the integral of f for any non-negative extended real-valued measurable function on E.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] For some functions, this integral ${\textstyle \int _{E}f\,d\mu }$ is infinite.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] It is often useful to have a particular sequence of simple functions that approximates the Lebesgue integral well (analogously to a Riemann sum).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] For a non-negative measurable function f, let *s**n*(*x*) be the simple function whose value is *k*/2*n* whenever *k*/2*n* ≤ *f*(*x*) < (*k* + 1)/2*n*, for k a non-negative integer less than, say, 4*n*.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Then it can be proven directly that $\int f\,d\mu =\lim _{n\to \infty }\int s_{n}\,d\mu$ and that the limit on the right hand side exists as an extended real number.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] This bridges the connection between the approach to the Lebesgue integral using simple functions, and the motivation for the Lebesgue integral using a partition of the range.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] To handle signed functions, we need a few more definitions.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Note that both *f*+ and *f*− are non-negative measurable functions.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] If $\int |f|\,\mathrm {d} \mu <\infty ,$ we say that f is *Lebesgue integrable*.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] It turns out that this definition gives the desirable properties of the integral.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Assuming that f is measurable and non-negative, the function $f^{*}(t)\ {\stackrel {\text{def}}{=}}\ \mu \left(\{x\in E\mid f(x)>t\}\right).$ is monotonically non-increasing.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The Lebesgue integral may then be defined as the improper Riemann integral of *f*∗: $\int _{E}f\,d\mu \ {\stackrel {\text{def}}{=}}\ \int _{0}^{\infty }f^{*}(t)\,dt.$ This integral is improper at the upper limit of ∞, and possibly also at zero.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] It exists, with the allowance that it may be infinite.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] As above, the integral of a Lebesgue integrable (not necessarily non-negative) function is defined by subtracting the integral of its positive and negative parts.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Complex-valued functions can be similarly integrated, by considering the real part and the imaginary part separately.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The function is Lebesgue integrable if and only if its absolute value is Lebesgue integrable (see Absolutely integrable function).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Consider the indicator function of the rational numbers, 1**Q**, also known as the Dirichlet function.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] A technical issue in Lebesgue integration is that the domain of integration is defined as a *set* (a subset of a measure space), with no notion of orientation.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] In elementary calculus, one defines integration with respect to an orientation: $\int _{b}^{a}f=-\int _{a}^{b}f.$ Generalizing this to higher dimensions yields integration of differential forms on manifolds, and to Stokes' theorem as the generalization of the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] By contrast, Lebesgue integration provides an alternative generalization, integrating over subsets with respect to a measure; this can be notated as $\int _{A}f\,d\mu =\int _{[a,b]}f\,d\mu$ to indicate integration over a subset A.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] For details on the relation between these generalizations, see Differential form § Relation with measures.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The main theory linking these ideas is that of homological integration (sometimes called geometric integration theory), pioneered by Georges de Rham and Hassler Whitney.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] With the advent of Fourier series, many analytical problems involving integrals arose whose satisfactory solution required interchanging limit processes and integral signs.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] However, the conditions under which the integrals $\sum _{k}\int f_{k}(x)\,dx\quad {\text{and}}\quad \int \left[\sum _{k}f_{k}(x)\right]dx$ are equal proved quite elusive in the Riemann framework.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] There are some other technical difficulties with the Riemann integral.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] These are linked with the limit-taking difficulty discussed above.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] As shown above, the indicator function 1**Q** on the rationals is not Riemann integrable.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] In particular, the Monotone convergence theorem fails.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] To see why, let {*a**k*} be an enumeration of all the rational numbers in [0, 1] (they are countable so this can be done).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The function gk is zero everywhere, except on a finite set of points.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Each gk is non-negative, and this sequence of functions is monotonically increasing, but its limit as *k* → ∞ is 1**Q**, which is not Riemann integrable.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The Riemann integral in its original form is defined over a closed bounded interval of the real line for real functions that are defined on the interval's entirety and continuous almost everywhere within it.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] It can, however, be extended to the complex plane, Euclidean space or unions of integrable regions with similar limitations.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] An improper Riemann integral, meanwhile, can integrate a function by taking limits on unbounded intervals or at points at which the function is not defined so long as the proper integral approaches a limit as the region of proper integration approaches the desired region of improper integration.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] While improper integration is an advantage of the Riemann integral, many Lebesgue-integrable functions are not well behaved enough or are defined on domains that are too irregular to be suitable for proper Riemann integration.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The Riemann integral is inextricably linked to the order structure of the real line.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Two functions are said to be equal almost everywhere ( $f\ {\stackrel {\text{a.e.}}{=}}\ g$ for short) if $\{x\mid f(x)\neq g(x)\}$ is a subset of a null set.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Measurability of the set $\{x\mid f(x)\neq g(x)\}$ is *not* required.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The following theorems are proved in most textbooks on measure theory and Lebesgue integration.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Necessary and sufficient conditions for the interchange of limits and integrals were proved by Cafiero, generalizing earlier work of Renato Caccioppoli, Vladimir Dubrovskii, and Gaetano Fichera.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] It is possible to develop the integral with respect to the Lebesgue measure without relying on the full machinery of measure theory.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] One such approach is provided by the Daniell integral.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] There is also an alternative approach to developing the theory of integration via methods of functional analysis.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The Riemann integral exists for any continuous function f of compact support defined on **R***n* (or a fixed open subset).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Integrals of more general functions can be built starting from these integrals.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Let *C*c be the space of all real-valued compactly supported continuous functions of **R**.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Then *C*c is a normed vector space (and in particular, it is a metric space.) All metric spaces have Hausdorff completions, so let *L*1 be its completion.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] This space is isomorphic to the space of Lebesgue integrable functions modulo the subspace of functions with integral zero.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Furthermore, the Riemann integral ∫ is a uniformly continuous functional with respect to the norm on *C*c, which is dense in *L*1.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] Hence ∫ has a unique extension to all of *L*1.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] This integral is precisely the Lebesgue integral.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] More precisely, the compactly supported functions form a vector space that carries a natural topology, and a (Radon) measure is defined as a continuous linear functional on this space.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The value of a measure at a compactly supported function is then also by definition the integral of the function.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] One then proceeds to expand the measure (the integral) to more general functions by continuity, and defines the measure of a set as the integral of its indicator function.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] This is the approach taken by Nicolas Bourbaki and a certain number of other authors.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] The main purpose of the Lebesgue integral is to provide an integral notion where limits of integrals hold under mild assumptions.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] There is no guarantee that every function is Lebesgue integrable.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] But it may happen that improper integrals exist for functions that are not Lebesgue integrable.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-integration] One example would be the sinc function: $\operatorname {sinc} (x)={\frac {\sin(x)}{x}}$ over the entire real line.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] In mathematics, **Lebesgue measure** is the standard way of assigning a notion of length to subsets of the real line, area to regions of the Euclidean plane, and volume to subsets of Euclidean space in dimensions three and higher.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] It is used throughout mathematical analysis, especially in the definition of the Lebesgue integral and in statements that hold "almost everywhere," meaning except on a set whose Lebesgue measure is zero.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Henri Lebesgue described this measure in the year 1901 which, a year after, was followed up by his description of the Lebesgue integral.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Both were published as part of his dissertation *Intégrale, Longueur, Aire* in 1902.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Lebesgue measure extends ordinary geometric length (or volume) in a way that is compatible with countable unions and other kinds of countable limits of sets.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] For example, every countable subset of the real line has Lebesgue measure zero, being a countable union of points, which have no length, while many uncountable sets also have measure zero.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The measure is not defined on every subset of the real line (or Euclidean space) under the usual axioms of set theory: the sets to which it applies are called Lebesgue-measurable.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The Lebesgue measure can then be obtained by *completing* this Borel measure, by assigning zero measure to all subsets of Borel sets that already have zero measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Lebesgue measure may be introduced as an extension of ordinary length, area, and volume.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] On the real line, the starting point is that an interval such as $[a,b]$ , $(a,b)$ , or $[a,b)$ should have length $b-a$ .
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] In $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , the corresponding elementary sets are rectangular boxes $B=I_{1}\times \cdots \times I_{n},$ where each $I_{i}$ is an interval.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The volume of such a box is $\operatorname {vol} (B)=\prod _{i=1}^{n}|I_{i}|.$ A construction related to the Lebesgue measure is the Jordan content, which approximates regions by finite partitions into rectangular boxes.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Similar to the Riemann integral, a set is Jordan measurable if there are such partitions that contain the region, and partitions contained within the region, that have an arbitrarily small difference between them.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Jordan measure is not as robust as the Lebesgue measure, because there are fairly basic sets that are not Jordan measurable, such as the set of rational numbers.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The first domain for the measure is the collection of Borel sets.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The Borel sets in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ form the smallest $\sigma$ -algebra containing all open sets.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Equivalently, they are the sets that can be obtained from open sets by applying countable unions, countable intersections, and complements.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] This includes open sets, closed sets, countable sets, intervals, boxes, and many other sets obtained from them by countable operations (e.g., the Cantor ternary set).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] There is a unique measure on the Borel subsets of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ that assigns to every rectangular box its usual volume and is invariant under translations.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] This is often called the Borel version of Lebesgue measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] However, as a measure on only the Borel sets, it is not complete: a subset of a Borel set of measure zero need not itself be Borel.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The Lebesgue-measurable sets are obtained by completing this Borel measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] That is, one adds to the Borel sets all subsets of Borel sets of measure zero, and all sets that differ from a Borel set by such a null set.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Equivalently, a set $E\subseteq \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is Lebesgue-measurable if there is a Borel set B such that the symmetric difference $E\triangle B=(E\setminus B)\cup (B\setminus E)$ has measure zero.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The Lebesgue measure of E is then defined to be the Borel measure of B .
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] This is well-defined because changing a set by a null set does not change its measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] For example, the Cantor set is a Borel set of Lebesgue measure zero.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Every subset of the Cantor set is therefore Lebesgue-measurable, even though not every such subset is a Borel set.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Thus the Lebesgue-measurable sets form a larger $\sigma$ -algebra than the Borel sets.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] For any interval $I=[a,b]$ , or $I=(a,b)$ , in the set $\mathbb {R}$ of real numbers, let $\ell (I)=b-a$ denote its length.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The above definition can be generalised to higher dimensions as follows.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] For any rectangular cuboid C which is a Cartesian product $C=I_{1}\times \cdots \times I_{n}$ of open intervals, let $\operatorname {vol} (C)=\ell (I_{1})\times \cdots \times \ell (I_{n})$ (a real number product) denote its volume.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Here, $E^{\complement }$ is the complement of E .
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Sets E satisfying the Carathéodory criterion are said to be *Lebesgue-measurable*.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The set of all such E forms a *σ*-algebra.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] ZFC proves that non-measurable sets do exist; examples are the Vitali sets.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The first part of the definition states that the subset E of the real numbers is reduced to its outer measure by coverage by sets of open intervals.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Each of these sets of intervals I covers E in a sense, since the union of these intervals contains E .
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The total length of any covering interval set may overestimate the measure of $E,$ because E is a subset of the union of the intervals, and so the intervals may include points which are not in E .
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The Lebesgue outer measure emerges as the greatest lower bound (infimum) of the lengths from among all possible such sets.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Intuitively, it is the total length of those interval sets which fit E most tightly and do not overlap.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] That characterizes the Lebesgue outer measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Whether this outer measure translates to the Lebesgue measure proper depends on an additional condition.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] This condition is tested by taking subsets A of the real numbers using E as an instrument to split A into two partitions: the part of A which intersects with E and the remaining part of A which is not in E : the set difference of A and E .
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] These partitions of A are subject to the outer measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] If for all possible such subsets A of the real numbers, the partitions of A cut apart by E have outer measures whose sum is the outer measure of A , then the outer Lebesgue measure of E gives its Lebesgue measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Intuitively, this condition means that the set E must not have some curious properties which causes a discrepancy in the measure of another set when E is used as a "mask" to "clip" that set, hinting at the existence of sets for which the Lebesgue outer measure does not give the Lebesgue measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] If *${\textstyle A}$* is a union of countably many pairwise disjoint Lebesgue-measurable sets, then *${\textstyle A}$* is itself Lebesgue-measurable and *${\textstyle \lambda (A)}$* is equal to the sum (or infinite series) of the measures of the involved measurable sets.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] If *${\textstyle A}$* is Lebesgue-measurable, then so is its complement.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] *${\textstyle \lambda (A)\geq 0}$* for every Lebesgue-measurable set *${\textstyle A}$*.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] If *${\textstyle A}$* and *${\textstyle B}$* are Lebesgue-measurable and *${\textstyle A}$* is a subset of *${\textstyle B}$*, then *${\textstyle \lambda (A)\leq \lambda (B)}$*.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Countable unions and intersections of Lebesgue-measurable sets are Lebesgue-measurable.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] If *${\textstyle A}$* is an open or closed subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ (or even Borel set, see metric space), then *${\textstyle A}$* is Lebesgue-measurable.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] If *${\textstyle A}$* is a Lebesgue-measurable set, then it is "approximately open" and "approximately closed" in the sense of Lebesgue measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] A Lebesgue-measurable set can be "squeezed" between a containing open set and a contained closed set.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] This property has been used as an alternative definition of Lebesgue measurability.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] More precisely, $E\subset \mathbb {R}$ is Lebesgue-measurable if and only if for every $\varepsilon >0$ there exist an open set G and a closed set F such that $F\subset E\subset G$ and $\lambda (G\setminus F)<\varepsilon$ .
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] A Lebesgue-measurable set can be "squeezed" between a containing G δ set and a contained F σ.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] I.e., if *${\textstyle A}$* is Lebesgue-measurable then there exist a G δ set *${\textstyle G}$* and an F σ *${\textstyle F}$* such that *${\textstyle F\subseteq A\subseteq G}$* and *${\textstyle \lambda (G\setminus A)=\lambda (A\setminus F)=0}$*.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Lebesgue measure is both locally finite and inner regular, and so it is a Radon measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Lebesgue measure is strictly positive on non-empty open sets, and so its support is the whole of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] If *${\textstyle A}$* is a Lebesgue-measurable set with *${\textstyle \lambda (A)=0}$* *(a null set),*then every subset of *${\textstyle A}$* is also a null set.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] *A fortiori*, every subset of A is measurable.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] If *${\textstyle A}$* is Lebesgue-measurable and *x* is an element of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , then the *translation of ${\textstyle A}$* *by ${\textstyle x}$*, defined by $A+x:=\{a+x:a\in A\}$ , is also Lebesgue-measurable and has the same measure as *${\textstyle A}$*.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] More generally, if *${\textstyle T}$* is a linear transformation and *${\textstyle A}$* is a measurable subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , then *${\textstyle T(A)}$* is also Lebesgue-measurable and has the measure $\left|\det(T)\right|\lambda (A)$ .
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The Lebesgue measure also has the property of being σ-finite.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] A subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is a *null set* if, for every $\varepsilon >0$ , it can be covered with countably many products of *n* intervals whose total volume is at most $\varepsilon$ .
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] If a subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ has Hausdorff dimension less than *n* then it is a null set with respect to *n*-dimensional Lebesgue measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Here Hausdorff dimension is relative to the Euclidean metric on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ (or any metric Lipschitz equivalent to it).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] On the other hand, a set may have topological dimension less than n and have positive *n*-dimensional Lebesgue measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] An example of this is the Smith–Volterra–Cantor set which has topological dimension 0 yet has positive 1-dimensional Lebesgue measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The modern construction of the Lebesgue measure is an application of Carathéodory's extension theorem.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] A **box** in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is a set of the form $B=\prod _{i=1}^{n}[a_{i},b_{i}]\,,$ where $b_{i}\geq a_{i}$ , and the product symbol here represents a Cartesian product.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The existence of sets that are not Lebesgue-measurable is a consequence of the set-theoretical axiom of choice, which is independent from many of the conventional systems of axioms for set theory.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The Vitali theorem, which follows from the axiom, states that there exist subsets of **$\mathbb {R}$** that are not Lebesgue-measurable.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Assuming the axiom of choice, non-measurable sets with many surprising properties have been demonstrated, such as those of the Banach–Tarski paradox.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] Solovay showed that the existence of sets that are not Lebesgue-measurable is not provable within the framework of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory in the absence of the axiom of choice (see Solovay's model).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The Borel measure agrees with the Lebesgue measure on those sets for which it is defined; however, there are many more Lebesgue-measurable sets than there are Borel measurable sets.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] While the Lebesgue measure on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is automatically a locally finite Borel measure, not every locally finite Borel measure on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is necessarily a Lebesgue measure.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The Borel measure is translation-invariant, but not complete.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The Haar measure can be defined on any locally compact group and is a generalization of the Lebesgue measure ( $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ with addition is a locally compact group).
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The Hausdorff measure is a generalization of the Lebesgue measure that is useful for measuring the subsets of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ of lower dimensions than *n*, like submanifolds, for example, surfaces or curves in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ and fractal sets.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] The Hausdorff measure is not to be confused with the notion of Hausdorff dimension.
[src:measure-theory/lebesgue-measure] It can be shown that there is no infinite-dimensional analogue of Lebesgue measure.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] In mathematics, the concept of a **measure** is a generalization and formalization of geometrical measures (length, area, volume) and other common notions, such as magnitude, mass, and probability of events.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] These seemingly distinct concepts have many similarities and can often be treated together in a single mathematical context.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Measures are foundational in probability theory, integration theory, and can be generalized to assume negative values, as with electrical charge.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Far-reaching generalizations (such as spectral measures and positive operator-valued measures) of measure are widely used in quantum physics and physics in general.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] The intuition behind this concept dates back to Ancient Greece, when Archimedes tried to calculate the area of a circle.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] But it was not until the late 19th and early 20th centuries that measure theory became a branch of mathematics.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] The foundations of modern measure theory were laid in the works of Émile Borel, Henri Lebesgue, Nikolai Luzin, Johann Radon, Constantin Carathéodory, and Maurice Fréchet, among others.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Let X be a set and $\Sigma$ a σ-algebra over X , defining subsets of X that are "measurable".
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Note that any sum involving $+\infty$ will equal $+\infty$ , that is, $a+\infty =+\infty$ for all a in the extended reals.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] If the condition of non-negativity is dropped, and $\mu (E)$ only ever equals one of $+\infty$ , $-\infty$ , i.e. no two distinct sets have measures $+\infty$ , $-\infty$ , respectively, then $\mu$ is called a *signed measure*.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] The pair $(X,\Sigma )$ is called a *measurable space*, and the members of $\Sigma$ are called **measurable sets**.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] A triple $(X,\Sigma ,\mu )$ is called a *measure space*.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] A probability measure is a measure with total measure one – that is, $\mu (X)=1.$ A probability space is a measure space with a probability measure.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] For measure spaces that are also topological spaces various compatibility conditions can be placed for the measure and the topology.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Most measures met in practice in analysis (and in many cases also in probability theory) are Radon measures (usually defined on Hausdorff spaces).
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] When working with locally compact Hausdorff spaces, Radon measures have an alternative, equivalent definition in terms of linear functionals on the locally convex topological vector space of continuous functions with compact support.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] This approach is taken by Bourbaki (2004) and a number of other sources.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] For more details, see the article on Radon measures.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Some important measures are listed here.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Other 'named' measures used in various theories include: Borel measure, Jordan measure, ergodic measure, Gaussian measure, Baire measure, Radon measure, Young measure, and Loeb measure.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] In physics an example of a measure is spatial distribution of mass (see for example, gravity potential), or another non-negative extensive property, conserved (see conservation law for a list of these) or not.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Negative values lead to signed measures, see "generalizations" below.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] This property is false without the assumption that at least one of the $E_{n}$ has finite measure.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] For instance, for each $n\in \mathbb {N} ,$ let $E_{n}=[n,\infty )\subseteq \mathbb {R} ,$ which all have infinite Lebesgue measure, but the intersection is empty.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] A measurable set X is called a *null set* if $\mu (X)=0.$ A subset of a null set is called a *negligible set*.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] A negligible set need not be measurable, but every measurable negligible set is automatically a null set.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] A measure is called *complete* if every negligible set is measurable.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] A measure can be extended to a complete one by considering the σ-algebra of subsets Y which differ by a negligible set from a measurable set $X,$ that is, such that the symmetric difference of X and Y is contained in a null set.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] If $f:X\to [0,+\infty ]$ is $(\Sigma ,{\cal {B}}([0,+\infty ]))$ -measurable, then $\mu \{x\in X:f(x)\geq t\}=\mu \{x\in X:f(x)>t\}$ for almost all $t\in [-\infty ,\infty ].$ This property is used in connection with Lebesgue integral.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Both $F(t):=\mu \{x\in X:f(x)>t\}$ and $G(t):=\mu \{x\in X:f(x)\geq t\}$ are monotonically non-increasing functions of $t,$ so both of them have at most countably many discontinuities and thus they are continuous almost everywhere, relative to the Lebesgue measure.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] If t is such that $\mu \{x\in X:f(x)>t\}=+\infty$ then monotonicity implies $\mu \{x\in X:f(x)\geq t\}=+\infty ,$ so that $F(t)=G(t),$ as required.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] If $\mu \{x\in X:f(x)>t\}=+\infty$ for all t then we are done, so assume otherwise.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Then there is a unique $t_{0}\in \{-\infty \}\cup [0,+\infty )$ such that F is infinite to the left of t (which can only happen when $t_{0}\geq 0$ ) and finite to the right.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Measures are required to be countably additive.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] However, the condition can be strengthened as follows.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] For any set I and any set of nonnegative $r_{i}$ where $i\in I$ define: $\sum _{i\in I}r_{i}=\sup \left\lbrace \sum _{i\in J}r_{i}:|J|<\infty ,J\subseteq I\right\rbrace .$ That is, we define the sum of the $r_{i}$ to be the supremum of all the sums of finitely many of them.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] A measure space $(X,\Sigma ,\mu )$ is called finite if $\mu (X)$ is a finite real number (rather than $\infty$ ).
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] A measure $\mu$ is called *σ-finite* if X can be decomposed into a countable union of measurable sets of finite measure.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] For example, the real numbers with the standard Lebesgue measure are σ-finite but not finite.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] The natural numbers are also σ-finite with respect to counting measure.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] However, the real numbers are not σ-finite with respect to counting measure.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Semifinite measures generalize sigma-finite measures, in such a way that some big theorems of measure theory that hold for sigma-finite but not arbitrary measures can be extended with little modification to hold for semifinite measures.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] The zero measure is sigma-finite and thus semifinite.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] We say the **semifinite part** of $\mu$ to mean the semifinite measure $\mu _{\text{sf}}$ defined in the above theorem.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Since $\mu _{\text{sf}}$ is semifinite, it follows that if $\mu =\mu _{\text{sf}}$ then $\mu$ is semifinite.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Every *$0-\infty$ measure* that is not the zero measure is not semifinite.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] (Here, we say *$0-\infty$ measure* to mean a measure whose range lies in $\{0,+\infty \}$ : $(\forall A\in {\cal {A}})(\mu (A)\in \{0,+\infty \}).$ ) Below we give examples of $0-\infty$ measures that are not zero measures.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] We say the **$\mathbf {0-\infty }$ part** of $\mu$ to mean the measure $\mu _{0-\infty }$ defined in the above theorem.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Localizable measures are a special case of semifinite measures and a generalization of sigma-finite measures.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] A measure is said to be s-finite if it is a countable sum of finite measures.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] S-finite measures are more general than sigma-finite ones and have applications in the theory of stochastic processes.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] If the axiom of choice is assumed to be true, it can be proved that not all subsets of Euclidean space are Lebesgue measurable; examples of such sets include the Vitali set, and the non-measurable sets postulated by the Hausdorff paradox and the Banach–Tarski paradox.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] For certain purposes, it is useful to have a "measure" whose values are not restricted to the non-negative reals or infinity.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] For instance, a countably additive set function with values in the (signed) real numbers is called a *signed measure*, while such a function with values in the complex numbers is called a *complex measure*.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Observe, however, that complex measure is necessarily of finite variation, hence complex measures include finite signed measures but not, for example, the Lebesgue measure.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Measures that take values in Banach spaces have been studied extensively.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] A measure that takes values in the set of self-adjoint projections on a Hilbert space is called a *projection-valued measure*; these are used in functional analysis for the spectral theorem.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] When it is necessary to distinguish the usual measures which take non-negative values from generalizations, the term **positive measure** is used.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Positive measures are closed under conical combination but not general linear combination, while signed measures are the linear closure of positive measures.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] More generally see measure theory in topological vector spaces.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Another generalization is the *finitely additive measure*, also known as a content.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] This is the same as a measure except that instead of requiring *countable* additivity we require only *finite* additivity.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Historically, this definition was used first.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] It turns out that in general, finitely additive measures are connected with notions such as Banach limits, the dual of $L^{\infty }$ and the Stone–Čech compactification.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] All these are linked in one way or another to the axiom of choice.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] Contents remain useful in certain technical problems in geometric measure theory; this is the theory of Banach measures.
[src:measure-theory/measure-mathematics] A *charge* is a generalization in both directions: it is a finitely additive, signed measure.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] In mathematics, the **Radon–Nikodym theorem**, named after Johann Radon and Otto M.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Nikodym, is a result in measure theory that expresses the relationship between two measures defined on the same measurable space.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] A *measure* is a set function that assigns a consistent magnitude to the measurable subsets of a measurable space.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Examples of a measure include area and volume, where the subsets are sets of points; or the probability of an event, which is a subset of possible outcomes within a wider probability space.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] One way to derive a new measure from one already given is to assign a density to each point of the space, then integrate over the measurable subset of interest.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] where $\nu$ is the new measure being defined for any measurable subset A and the function f is the density at a given point.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] The integral is with respect to an existing measure $\mu$ , which may often be the canonical Lebesgue measure on the real line $\mathbb {R}$ or the n -dimensional Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ (corresponding to our standard notions of length, area and volume).
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] For example, if f represented mass density and $\mu$ was the Lebesgue measure in three-dimensional space $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ , then $\nu (A)$ would equal the total mass in a spatial region A .
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] The Radon–Nikodym theorem essentially states that, under certain conditions, any measure $\nu$ can be expressed in this way with respect to another measure $\mu$ on the same space.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] The function f is then called the **Radon–Nikodym derivative** and is denoted by $d\nu /d\mu$ .
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] An important application is in probability theory, leading to the probability density function of a random variable.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] The theorem is named after Johann Radon, who proved the theorem for the special case where the underlying space is $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ in 1913, and for Otto Nikodym who proved the general case in 1930.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] In 1936, Hans Freudenthal generalized the Radon–Nikodym theorem by proving the Freudenthal spectral theorem, a result in Riesz space theory; this contains the Radon–Nikodym theorem as a special case.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] A Banach space Y is said to have the Radon–Nikodym property if the generalization of the Radon–Nikodym theorem also holds (with the necessary adjustments made) for functions with values in Y .
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] All Hilbert spaces have the Radon–Nikodym property.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] The function f satisfying the above equality is *uniquely defined up to a $\mu$ -null set*, that is, if g is another function which satisfies the same property, then $f=g$ $\mu$ -almost everywhere.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] The function f is commonly written $d\nu /d\mu$ and is called the **Radon–Nikodym derivative**.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] In the following examples, the set X is the real interval $[0,1]$ , and $\Sigma$ is the Borel sigma-algebra on X .
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Let $\mu$ be the length measure on X , and let $\nu$ assign to each subset Y of X the number of points from the set $\{0.1,\dots ,0.9\}$ that are contained in Y .
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Then $\nu$ is not absolutely continuous with respect to $\mu$ since it assigns non-zero measure to zero-length points.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Indeed, there is no derivative ${\textstyle {\frac {d\nu }{d\mu }}}$ : there is no finite function that, when integrated e.g. from $(0.1-\varepsilon )$ to $(0.1+\varepsilon )$ , gives 1 for all $\varepsilon >0$ .
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] 3. $\mu =\nu +\delta _{0}$ , where $\nu$ is the length measure on X and $\delta _{0}$ is the Dirac measure on 0 (it assigns a measure of 1 to any set containing 0 and a measure of 0 to any other set).
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Then, $\nu$ is absolutely continuous with respect to $\mu$ , and ${\textstyle {\frac {d\nu }{d\mu }}=1_{X\setminus \{0\}}}$ – the derivative is 0 at $x=0$ and 1 at $x>0$ .
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] The theorem is very important in extending the ideas of probability theory from probability masses and probability densities defined over real numbers to probability measures defined over arbitrary sets.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] It tells if and how it is possible to change from one probability measure to another.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Specifically, the probability density function of a random variable is the Radon–Nikodym derivative of the induced measure with respect to some base measure (usually the Lebesgue measure for continuous random variables).
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] For example, it can be used to prove the existence of conditional expectation for probability measures.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] The latter itself is a key concept in probability theory, as conditional probability is just a special case of it.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Amongst other fields, financial mathematics uses the theorem extensively, in particular via the Girsanov theorem.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Such changes of probability measure are the cornerstone of the rational pricing of derivatives and are used for converting actual probabilities into those of the risk neutral probabilities.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] The Radon–Nikodym theorem above makes the assumption that the measure *μ* with respect to which one computes the rate of change of *ν* is σ-finite.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Here is an example when *μ* is not σ-finite and the Radon–Nikodym theorem fails to hold.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Consider the Borel σ-algebra on the real line.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Let the counting measure, μ, of a Borel set A be defined as the number of elements of A if A is finite, and ∞ otherwise.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] One can check that μ is indeed a measure.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] It is not σ-finite, as not every Borel set is at most the union of countably many finite sets.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Let ν be the usual Lebesgue measure on this Borel algebra.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Then, ν is absolutely continuous with respect to μ, since for a set A one has *μ*(*A*) = 0 only if A is the empty set, and then *ν*(*A*) is also zero.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] This implies that the function *f* , and therefore the Lebesgue measure ν, is zero, which is a contradiction.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] This section gives a measure-theoretic proof of the theorem.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] There is also a functional-analytic proof, using Hilbert space methods, that was first given by von Neumann.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] For finite measures μ and ν, the idea is to consider functions *f* with *f dμ* ≤ *dν*.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] The supremum of all such functions, along with the monotone convergence theorem, then furnishes the Radon–Nikodym derivative.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] The fact that the remaining part of μ is singular with respect to ν follows from a technical fact about finite measures.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Once the result is established for finite measures, extending to σ-finite, signed, and complex measures can be done naturally.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] By replacing *fn* with the maximum of the first n functions, one can assume that the sequence { *fn* } is increasing.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] To prove equality, we show that *ν*0 = 0.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Suppose ν0 ≠ 0; then, since μ is finite, there is an *ε* > 0 such that *ν*0(*X*) > *ε μ*(*X*).
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] To derive a contradiction from ν0 ≠ 0, we look for a positive set *P* ∈ Σ for the signed measure *ν*0 − *ε μ* (i.e. a measurable set P, all of whose measurable subsets have non-negative *ν*0 − *εμ* measure), where also P has positive μ-measure.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Conceptually, we're looking for a set P, where *ν*0 ≥ *ε μ* in every part of P.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] A convenient approach is to use the Hahn decomposition (*P*, *N*) for the signed measure *ν*0 − *ε μ*.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] where 1*P* is the indicator function of P.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] This is impossible because it violates the definition of a supremum; therefore, the initial assumption that *ν*0 ≠ 0 must be false.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] and so, that (*g* − *f* )+ = 0 μ-almost everywhere; the same is true for (*g* − *f* )−, and thus, *f* = *g* μ-almost everywhere, as desired.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] If μ and ν are σ-finite, then X can be written as the union of a sequence {*Bn*}*n* of disjoint sets in Σ, each of which has finite measure under both μ and ν.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] The sum ${\textstyle \left(\sum _{n}f_{n}1_{B_{n}}\right):=f}$ of those functions is then the required function such that ${\textstyle \nu (A)=\int _{A}f\,d\mu }$ .
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] As for the uniqueness, since each of the *fn* is μ-almost everywhere unique, so is *f*.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] If ν is a σ-finite signed measure, then it can be Hahn–Jordan decomposed as *ν* = *ν*+ − *ν*− where one of the measures is finite.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Applying the previous result to those two measures, one obtains two functions, *g*, *h* : *X* → [0, ∞), satisfying the Radon–Nikodym theorem for *ν*+ and *ν*− respectively, at least one of which is μ-integrable (i.e., its integral with respect to μ is finite).
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] It is clear then that *f* = *g* − *h* satisfies the required properties, including uniqueness, since both g and h are unique up to μ-almost everywhere equality.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] If ν is a complex measure, it can be decomposed as *ν* = *ν*1 + *iν*2, where both *ν*1 and *ν*2 are finite-valued signed measures.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Applying the above argument, one obtains two functions, *g*, *h* : *X* → [0, ∞), satisfying the required properties for *ν*1 and *ν*2, respectively.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Clearly, *f* = *g* + *ih* is the required function.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Lebesgue's decomposition theorem shows that the assumptions of the Radon–Nikodym theorem can be found even in a situation which is seemingly more general.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] Consider a σ-finite positive measure $\mu$ on the measure space $(X,\Sigma )$ and a σ-finite signed measure $\nu$ on $\Sigma$ , without assuming any absolute continuity.
[src:measure-theory/radon-nikodym-theorem] The Radon–Nikodym theorem can then be applied to the pair $\nu _{a},\mu$ .
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] In mathematical analysis and in probability theory, a **σ-algebra** ("sigma algebra") is part of the formalism for defining sets that can be measured.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] In calculus and analysis, for example, σ-algebras are used to define the concept of sets with area or volume.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] In probability theory, they are used to define events for which a probability can be defined.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] In this way, σ-algebras help to formalize the notion of *size*.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] In formal terms, a σ-algebra (also **σ-field**, where the σ comes from the German *Summe*, meaning "sum") on a set X is a nonempty collection $\Sigma$ of subsets of X closed under complement, countable unions, and countable intersections.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The ordered pair $(X,\Sigma )$ is called a measurable space.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The set X is understood to be an ambient space (such as the 2D plane or the set of outcomes when rolling a six-sided die $\{1,2,3,4,5,6\}$ ), and the collection $\Sigma$ is a choice of subsets declared to have a well-defined size.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] In general, a finite algebra is always a σ-algebra.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] If $\{A_{1},A_{2},A_{3},\ldots \},$ is a countable partition of X then the collection of all unions of sets in the partition (including the empty set) is a σ-algebra.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] There are at least three key motivators for σ-algebras: defining measures, manipulating limits of sets, and managing partial information characterized by sets.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] A measure on X is a function that assigns a non-negative real number to subsets of $X;$ this can be thought of as making precise a notion of "size" or "volume" for sets.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] We want the size of the union of disjoint sets to be the sum of their individual sizes, even for an infinite sequence of disjoint sets.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] One would like to assign a size to *every* subset of $X,$ but in many natural settings, this is not possible.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] For example, the axiom of choice implies that when the size under consideration is the ordinary notion of length for subsets of the real line, then there exist sets for which no size exists, for example, the Vitali sets.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] For this reason, one considers instead a smaller collection of privileged subsets of $X.$ These subsets will be called the measurable sets.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] They are closed under operations that one would expect for measurable sets, that is, the complement of a measurable set is a measurable set and the countable union of measurable sets is a measurable set.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] Non-empty collections of sets with these properties are called σ-algebras.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] Many uses of measure, such as the probability concept of almost sure convergence, involve limits of sequences of sets.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] For this, closure under countable unions and intersections is paramount.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] Set limits are defined as follows on σ-algebras.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] In much of probability, especially when conditional expectation is involved, one is concerned with sets that represent only part of all the possible information that can be observed.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] This partial information can be characterized with a smaller σ-algebra which is a subset of the principal σ-algebra; it consists of the collection of subsets relevant only to and determined only by the partial information.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] Formally, if $\Sigma ,\Sigma '$ are σ-algebras on X , then $\Sigma '$ is a sub σ-algebra of $\Sigma$ if $\Sigma '\subseteq \Sigma$ .
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The Bernoulli process provides a simple example.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] This consists of a sequence of random coin flips, coming up Heads ( H ) or Tails ( T ), of unbounded length.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The full sigma algebra can be generated from an ascending sequence of subalgebras, by considering the information that might be obtained after observing some or all of the first n coin flips.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The first subalgebra ${\mathcal {G}}_{0}=\{\varnothing ,\Omega \}$ is the trivial algebra: it has only two elements in it, the empty set and the total space.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The second subalgebra ${\mathcal {G}}_{1}$ has four elements: the two in ${\mathcal {G}}_{0}$ plus two more: sequences that start with H and sequences that start with T .
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The n th subalgebra contains $2^{n+1}$ elements: it divides the total space $\Omega$ into all of the possible sequences that might have been observed after n flips, including the possible non-observation of some of the flips.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The limiting algebra ${\mathcal {G}}_{\infty }$ is the smallest σ-algebra containing all the others.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] Let X be some set, and let $P(X)$ represent its power set, the set of all subsets of X .
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] From these properties, it follows that the σ-algebra is also closed under countable intersections (by applying De Morgan's laws).
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] Elements of the σ-algebra are called measurable sets.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] An ordered pair $(X,\Sigma ),$ where X is a set and $\Sigma$ is a σ-algebra over $X,$ is called a **measurable space**.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] A function between two measurable spaces is called a measurable function if the preimage of every measurable set is measurable.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The collection of measurable spaces forms a category, with the measurable functions as morphisms.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] A σ-algebra is both a π-system and a Dynkin system (λ-system).
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The converse is true as well, by Dynkin's theorem (see below).
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] This theorem (or the related monotone class theorem) is an essential tool for proving many results about properties of specific σ-algebras.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] It capitalizes on the nature of two simpler classes of sets, namely the following.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] One of the most fundamental uses of the π-λ theorem is to show equivalence of separately defined measures or integrals.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The intersection of a collection of σ-algebras is a σ-algebra.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] Suppose Y is a subset of X and let $(X,\Sigma )$ be a measurable space.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] If, instead of zero measure, one takes measurable subsets of finite Lebesgue measure, those are a ring but not a *σ*-ring, since the real line can be obtained by their countable union yet its measure is not finite.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] Any $\sigma$ -algebra generated by a countable collection of sets is separable, but the converse need not hold.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] For example, the Lebesgue $\sigma$ -algebra is separable (since every Lebesgue measurable set is equivalent to some Borel set) but not countably generated (since its cardinality is higher than continuum).
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] A separable measure space has a natural pseudometric that renders it separable as a pseudometric space.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The distance between two sets is defined as the measure of the symmetric difference of the two sets.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The symmetric difference of two distinct sets can have measure zero; hence the pseudometric as defined above need not be a true metric.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] However, if sets whose symmetric difference has measure zero are identified into a single equivalence class, the resulting quotient set can be properly metrized by the induced metric.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] If the measure space is separable, it can be shown that the corresponding metric space is, too.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] Let F be an arbitrary family of subsets of $X.$ Then there exists a unique smallest σ-algebra which contains every set in F (even though F may or may not itself be a σ-algebra).
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] If F is empty, then $\sigma (\varnothing )=\{\varnothing ,X\}.$ Otherwise $\sigma (F)$ consists of all the subsets of X that can be made from elements of F by a countable number of complement, union and intersection operations.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] There are many families of subsets that generate useful σ-algebras.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] Let $\left(X,\Sigma _{X}\right)$ , $\left(S,\Sigma _{S}\right)$ and $\left(T,\Sigma _{T}\right)$ be measurable spaces and let $f:X\to S$ and $g:X\to T$ be measurable maps between them.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] If there exists a third measurable map $h:T\to S$ such that $f=h\circ g$ , then $\sigma (f)\subseteq \sigma (g).$ Furthermore, if S is countable or, more generally, if $\left(S,\Sigma _{S}\right)$ is a standard Borel space, then the converse also holds.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] An example of a standard Borel space would be any separable complete metric space, like $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , with its associated Borel sets.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] Another example is $\mathbb {R} ^{\infty }$ with the cylinder σ-algebra described below.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] An important example is the Borel algebra over any topological space: the σ-algebra generated by the open sets (or, equivalently, by the closed sets).
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] This σ-algebra is not, in general, the whole power set.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] For a non-trivial example that is not a Borel set, see the Vitali set or Non-Borel sets.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] On the Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n},$ another σ-algebra is of importance: that of all Lebesgue measurable sets.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] This σ-algebra contains more sets than the Borel σ-algebra on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and is preferred in integration theory, as it gives a complete measure space.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The Borel σ-algebra for $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is generated by half-infinite rectangles and by finite rectangles.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] For each of these two examples, the generating family is a π-system.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] An important special case is when $\mathbb {T}$ is the set of natural numbers and X is a set of real-valued sequences.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The ball σ-algebra is the smallest σ-algebra containing all the open (and/or closed) balls.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] This is never larger than the Borel σ-algebra.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] Note that the two σ-algebra are equal for separable spaces.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] For some nonseparable spaces, some maps are ball measurable even though they are not Borel measurable, making use of the ball σ-algebra useful in the analysis of such maps.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] Suppose $(\Omega ,\Sigma ,\mathbb {P} )$ is a probability space.
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] If $\textstyle Y:\Omega \to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is measurable with respect to the Borel σ-algebra on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ then Y is called a **random variable** ( $n=1$ ) or **random vector** ( $n>1$ ).
[src:measure-theory/sigma-algebra] The σ-algebra generated by Y is $\sigma (Y)=\left\{Y^{-1}(A):A\in \sigma \left({\mathcal {F}}_{X}\right)\right\}=\sigma \left(\left\{Y^{-1}(A):A\in {\mathcal {F}}_{X}\right\}\right),$ the σ-algebra generated by the inverse images of cylinder sets.
